    {
      "beat_id": "B02",
      "t_start": 7.0,
      "estimated_duration_s": 11,
      "narration_text": "Draw the energy levels for a particle in a box. The rungs climb upward — and the lowest one is not at the floor. It floats above zero. That gap is the zero-point energy.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "Create"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B02.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 9.86,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B02.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T12:12:16"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B03",
      "t_start": 18.0,
      "estimated_duration_s": 9,
      "narration_text": "Classical reasoning: a particle at rest has zero kinetic energy. Make the box smaller, slow it down more, bring it to a complete stop. Energy should be zero.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "card": {
        "eyebrow": "THE QUESTION",
        "headline": "Classically, a particle at rest has zero energy. Here the ground state always floats above zero. Why can't the bottom rung sit on the floor?",
        "dek": ""
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B03.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 9.3,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B03.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T12:12:16"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B04",
      "t_start": 27.0,
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "Classical picture: shrink the box, slow the particle, remove energy until it stops. Zero energy is reachable. The floor is the floor.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "Create"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B04.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 8.13,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B04.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T12:12:16"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B05",
      "t_start": 37.0,
      "estimated_duration_s": 11,
      "narration_text": "But a trapped particle is a wave. The wavefunction must go to zero at both walls — that is the boundary condition. A wave that hits zero at both ends must fit a whole half-wavelength inside.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "animate"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B05.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 11.03,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B05.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T12:12:16"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B06",
      "t_start": 48.0,
      "estimated_duration_s": 7,
      "narration_text": "The curvature is the energy.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "card": {
        "eyebrow": "THE MECHANISM",
        "headline": "Fitting the half-wave\nforces curvature — curvature is kinetic energy",
        "dek": ""
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B06.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 2.37,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B06.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T12:12:16"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B07",
      "t_start": 55.0,
      "estimated_duration_s": 13,
      "narration_text": "A flat wave has zero curvature and zero kinetic energy. But a wave that curves — that bends to hit zero at both walls — has curvature. The Schrodinger equation says curvature is kinetic energy. The more curved the wave, the higher the energy.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "animate"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B07.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 14.21,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B07.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T12:12:16"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B08",
      "t_start": 68.0,
      "estimated_duration_s": 11,
      "narration_text": "The ground state fits exactly one half-wavelength. Shrink the box and that half-wave must squeeze tighter — it curves more, so its kinetic energy rises. The energy floor goes up as one over L squared.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "animate"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B08.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 11.54,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B08.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T12:12:16"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B09",
      "t_start": 79.0,
      "estimated_duration_s": 7,
      "narration_text": "Confinement creates the energy floor.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "card": {
        "eyebrow": "THE IMPLICATION",
        "headline": "Tighter box,\nhigher floor",
        "dek": ""
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B09.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 2.86,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B09.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T12:12:16"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B10",
      "t_start": 86.0,
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "This is not a quirk of boxes. Every confined quantum system has a positive energy floor — a zero-point energy. Liquid helium refuses to freeze at absolute zero because the zero-point motion of helium atoms prevents them from locking into a lattice.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "STILL",
        "source": "ai",
        "motion": "hold",
        "remotion": {
          "pattern": "SlateCard",
          "provenance": "proven-core/SlateCard",
